An interactive graphic in three four a few lines of code¶

In [ ]:
import altair as alt

alt.Chart(df_cars).mark_circle().encode(
    x="Horsepower",  # X axis variable!
    y="Miles_per_Gallon",  # Y axis variable!
    color="Origin",  # Colour variable!
)

👩‍💻👨‍💻 Workflow for private collaborative data reporting¶

Create a secret gist¶

  1. Login to github.com (github.com/login).
  2. Click the plus menu in the top right corner then ‘New gist’.
  1. In the text box where it says ‘Filename including extension…’, give your gist the filename ira-users-hashed.csv. The filename must end in .csv for it to format correctly on GitHub.
  2. Open your local copy of ira-users-hashed.csv in whichever of the text editors on your machine you like (you should find that Atom, Sublime Text and Visual Studio Code are all installed). Select the entire contents of the file (Command-A) then copy them to the clipboard (Command-C).
  3. Paste the contents of the file into the text box (where there's a 1).
  1. Click ‘Create secret gist’. You should see some nicely formatted data!
  2. Click the ‘Raw’ button to navigate to the plain text URL of your new gist and copy the URL to the clipboard.

Reverse-engineer account creation date¶

In [ ]:
df_twitter["date_created"] = df_twitter["days_active"].apply(
    lambda d: pd.to_datetime("2018-10-01") - pd.DateOffset(days=d)
)

df_twitter.head()

Plot using Altair¶

In [ ]:
alt.Chart(df_twitter).mark_circle(size=60).encode(
    x="date_created:T",
    y="tweet_count:Q",
    color="account_language:N",
    tooltip=["date_created", "tweet_count", "account_language"],
).interactive().properties(width=600, height=400)

Create empty map¶

In [ ]:
from keplergl import KeplerGl

kepler_map = KeplerGl(height=600)
config = {
    "version": "v1",
    "config": {
        "mapState": {
            "latitude": 29.9511,
            "longitude": -90.0715,
            "zoom": 5,
        }
    }
}
kepler_map.config = config

kepler_map

User Guide: https://github.com/keplergl/kepler.gl/blob/master/docs/keplergl-jupyter/user-guide.md

Add data to map¶

In [ ]:
kepler_map.add_data(
    data=df_ghosn.query("baroaltitude == baroaltitude"),
    name="Ghosn",
)

kepler_map

Save map to HTML¶

In [ ]:
kepler_map.save_to_html(
    data={"Ghosn transponder data": df_ghosn},
    config=config,
    file_name="kepler_map.html",
)

Map saved to kepler_map.html!

  1. Click on the Jupyter logo in the top left corner to see all the files in the current project (just click yes if it asks you if you're sure).
  2. Click on kepler_map.html.
